   (ICDCS), Jersey, NJ, JUL 23-26, 2024},
Organization = {IEEE; IEEE Comp Soc; IEEE Tech Comm Distributed Proc; US Natl Sci Fdn;
   New Jersey Inst Technol, Ying Wu Coll Comp},
Abstract = {As modern applications are being designed in a distributed,
   Microservices Architecture (MSA), it becomes increasingly difficult to
   debug and test those systems. Typically, it is the role of software
   testing engineers or Quality Assurance (QA) engineers to write software
   tests to ensure the reliability of applications, but such a task can be
   labor-intensive and time-consuming. In this paper, we explore the
   potential of Large Language Models (LLMs) in assisting software
   engineers in generating test cases for software systems, with a
   particular focus on performing end-to-end (black-box) system testing on
   web-based MSA applications. We present our experience building Kashef, a
   software testing tool that utilizes the advanced capabilities of current
   LLMs in code generation and reasoning, and builds on top of the concept
   of communicative agents.},
